liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: An inquiry is set to be announced into the state, territory and federal governments' response to the COVID-19 pandemic. Prime Minister Anthony Albanese and Health Minister Mark Butler will announce the inquiry in Adelaide this morning. The ABC understands the inquiry will not have the same powers as a royal commission but will be able to call witnesses and examine the response of federal, state and territory governments during the pandemic. The inquiry will cover all responses since the COVID-19 pandemic began in January 2020. The terms of the inquiry will be further fleshed out by the prime minister and Mr Butler but the ABC understands the probe will be led by medical experts. You can follow the latest updates on this below:
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Anthony Albanese to announce inquiry into COVID-19 response

featuredLink.title: Government to launch inquiry into federal, state and territory response to pandemic

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Authorities in New South Wales say it will take several days to bring fires under control as a cool change moves through the state. The north-western region of the state is under a total fire ban today, with hot and windy conditions forecast. More than 60 fires are still burning following above-average September heat during the first half of the week. Meanwhile, fire crews in Queensland are on stand-by for worsening conditions today, with parts of the coast expecting record temperatures of 40C. There are total fire bans for the Barcoo shire in the state's south-west. Queensland has been battling multiple bushfires since the weekend, with a firefighting helicopter pilot having a lucky escape after crashing into a dam.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Fire authorities in Queensland and NSW still on high alert

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Elon Musk's brain-chip startup Neuralink says it will begin recruiting for the first human trial of its brain implant for paralysis patients. The company received approval from an independent review board in May, though it's not known how many patients have ultimately been approved for the trial. The study will use a robot to surgically place a brain-computer interface implant in a region of the brain that controls the intention to move. Neuralink says the the goal is to allow those with paralysis to control a computer cursor or keyboard using their thoughts alone. Musk has grand ambitions for the company, saying it will facilitate speedy surgical insertions of its chip devices to treat conditions like obesity, autism, depression and schizophrenia. Here's Ryan Merkley from the Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine explaining how the implant would work and the ethical concerns it raises:

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The proposed move to establish a separate body within the Reserve Bank to make interest rates decisions in future would be a "very bad policy" and "a leap of faith" which would undermine the authority of the RBA governor, according to former governor Ian Macfarlane. Implementing the recommendations of a review into the bank's operations — including establishing the new decision-making board — is regarded as one of the big challenges facing new RBA governor Michele Bullock, who started in the job this week. liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The US central bank held interest rates steady as expected at the end of a two-day policy meeting, but the rate-setting Federal Open Market Committee said "inflation remains elevated" and Fed chair Jerome Powell said the Fed's job is to lower it. "We are committed to achieving and sustaining sufficiently restrictive policy to bring inflation down to 2 per cent over time," Powell said at a press conference, adding that reducing inflation is likely to require a period of below trend growth. The Fed's announcement was accompanied by its Summary Economic Projections (SEP) and dot plot, which sees an additional 25 basis point rate hike this year, peaking in the 5.5 to 5.75 per cent range. Fed officials now see the personal consumption expenditures price index at 3.3 per cent at year end, up from June's forecast of 3.2 per cent, and its overnight lending rate to be 5.1 per cent at the end of 2024, about 50 basis points higher than futures have projected. "The Fed is trying to send as hawkish a signal as it possibly can. It's just a question of whether the markets will listen to them without taking them with a grain of salt," said Gennadiy Goldberg, head of US interest rate strategy at TD Securities in New York. "They're talking about higher rates for longer, but it's really the economy that matters. And if the economy starts to soften, I don't think these dot plot projections will actually hold up."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: US Fed sees 25 bp hike this year, 50 bp cuts in 2024

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Good morning and welcome to today's markets live blog, where we'll bring you the latest price action and news on the ASX and beyond. A tumble on Wall Street overnight set the tone for local market action today. The Dow Jones index dropped 0.2 per cent, the S & P 500 lost 0.9 per cent and the Nasdaq Composite was down 1.5 per cent. ASX futures were down 20 points or 0.2 per cent to 7,151 at 7:30am AEST. At the same time, the Australian dollar was flat at 64.46 US cents.
